{"id":"7258","name":"Pediatric GCS","tagline":"Pediatric Glasgow Coma Scale (PGCS) for Health Care Providers","icon":"ios14 c4292093695 g59687","latest":"23174","description":"\n\t\t\t\t\t<p><a href=\"https://ibb.co/dpfqThD\"><img alt=\"4-DB3-A049-1-C3-F-461-A-B7-B0-EDAD66-ABFAB0\" src=\"https://i.ibb.co/xg20k46/4-DB3-A049-1-C3-F-461-A-B7-B0-EDAD66-ABFAB0.png\"></a></p>\n<ul>\n<li>\n<h6>You can run the Shortcut by saying this phrase to Siri “Pediatric GCS” or add the Shortcut to home screen and run it from there.</h6>\n</li>\n<li>After receiving the PGCS score the Shortcut will ask you if you want to save the result to Notes with a Timestamp so you can get the result when ever you want.</li>\n<li>The Pediatric Glasgow Coma Scale (PGCS):\nis scored between 3 and 15, with 3 being the worst and 15 the best. </li>\n<li>It is composed of 3 parameters: <ul>\n<li>Best eye response (E)</li>\n<li>Best verbal response (V)</li>\n<li>Best motor response (M)</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>The components of the PGCS should be recorded individually; for example, E2V3M4 results in a PGCS of 9. A score of 13 or higher correlates with mild brain injury, a score of 9 to 12 correlates with moderate injury, and a score of 8 or less represents severe brain injury.</li>\n<li>The Pediatric Glasgow Coma Scale (PGCS) was validated in children 2 years of age or younger.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr>\n<h5>Screenshots :</h5>\n<p><a href=\"https://ibb.co/94Cz72z\"><img alt=\"3-EEE7-ACE-F771-4-D1-F-BC0-B-BC1-A68-F8-EF80\" src=\"https://i.ibb.co/s1MkZQk/3-EEE7-ACE-F771-4-D1-F-BC0-B-BC1-A68-F8-EF80.png\"></a></p>\n<p><a href=\"https://ibb.co/Hgyn9B7\"><img alt=\"86-A26241-94-FF-40-B8-A197-C7-CD496-B3-CA9\" src=\"https://i.ibb.co/LpynsYS/86-A26241-94-FF-40-B8-A197-C7-CD496-B3-CA9.png\"></a></p>\n<hr>\n<h5>If this is your first time using Shortcuts you have to activate \"<em>Allow Untrusted Shortcuts</em>\" by going to</h5>\n<p><strong>Settings -&gt; Shortcuts and enable \"Allow Untrusted Shortcuts\"</strong>.</p>\n<p>